{
  "stem": "17526.5",
  "chunk_idx": 13,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 7.8,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "The building dates back to 1574 and that one was called the new shul.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "The one from 1574 was called the new shul.",
      "word_count": 9
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "The one we couldn't get inside when we first got there was the old shul.",
      "word_count": 15
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "As we looked around, we saw a group of 15 to 20 old people praying.",
      "word_count": 15
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 5,
      "text": "They had just about finished reading the Torah.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "I was asked if I could assist them in lifting the Torah, and I gladly volunteered.",
      "word_count": 16
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 7,
      "text": "I was also given the honor to conduct the rest of the services.",
      "word_count": 13
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 8,
      "text": "They seemed to have liked my performance very much.",
      "word_count": 9
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 9,
      "text": "As I stood in front of the altar and looked at the walls; the pews, the benches, the architecture, the eternal light, the [NON-ENGLISH], and the matching wrinkled faces of my co-worshippers, I could not help not feeling electrified emotionally when a feeling overwhelmed me.",
      "word_count": 45
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 10,
      "text": "All I could think of was, if only these walls could talk, if they could reveal the events that they were witness of-- the joys and the sorrows, the happiness, the tragedies, the pleasures and misfortunes, the tears that were spilled here, the ecstasy of old prayers, the rivalries among its worshippers, the happy holidays, the brisses, the bar mitzvahs, the weddings, [INAUDIBLE], nights, the [INAUDIBLE] nights, the funerals, the eulogies, and the great rabbis-- the Hazzanim, the cantors, and above all the [INAUDIBLE], the children, the [NON-ENGLISH], the [NON-ENGLISH], the [?",
      "word_count": 92
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 11,
      "text": "Yankele, ?] the [NON-ENGLISH], the [NON-ENGLISH], and the [NON-ENGLISH].",
      "word_count": 9
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 12,
      "text": "All these scenes suddenly appeared and came to haunt me.",
      "word_count": 10
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 13,
      "text": "I felt like I was surrounded by them, all in one big circle spinning through generations.",
      "word_count": 16
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 16,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 14,
      "text": "And then as the circle was breaking up, I was left with a few broken pieces of the remnants of that great Polish Jewry.",
      "word_count": 24
    }
  ],
